      "solution": "<p>When (1-methylcyclopentyl) methanol is \ntreated with H$$^+$$ at high temperature, it is \nconverted to 1-methyl-1-cyclohexene.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9l0qcr/fb8d4a2c-9d9d-4610-8d39-960d8745c503/56f473b0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l0qcs.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9l0qcr/fb8d4a2c-9d9d-4610-8d39-960d8745c503/56f473b0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l0qcs.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 10 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>Therefore, X is 1-methyl-1-cyclohexene.</p>\n<p>The mechanism for the same is represented \nbelow.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9l1t16/7b37dbe8-9726-4860-9771-5fa264bb602c/74d539a0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l1t17.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9l1t16/7b37dbe8-9726-4860-9771-5fa264bb602c/74d539a0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l1t17.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 10 English Explanation 2\"></p>\n<p>The H$$^+$$ on heating with (1-methylcyclopentyl)\nmethanol get attached to O atom of hydroxy \ngroup, producing a positive charge on O atom. \nThe elimination of water molecule results \nin the formation of primary carbocation, \nwhich undergoes ring expansion followed by \nelimination of proton yields product X.</p>\n<p>The 1-methyl-1-cyclohexene undergoes \nozonolysis followed by treatment with Zn/\nCH$$_3$$COOH, it gives 6-oxoheptanal.\n</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9l35xm/27d4223b-294e-490e-8f5d-4b62af351671/9a9ba2a0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l35xn.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9l35xm/27d4223b-294e-490e-8f5d-4b62af351671/9a9ba2a0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l35xn.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 10 English Explanation 3\"></p>\n<p>Therefore, compound Y is 6-oxoheptanal</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9l4i8q/9b951c2b-ad54-4695-a278-725d4cbe5c5a/bfecdba0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l4i8r.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9l4i8q/9b951c2b-ad54-4695-a278-725d4cbe5c5a/bfecdba0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9l4i8r.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 10 English Explanation 4\"></p>\n<p>Y on further undergoes aldol condensation \nreaction to form $$\\alpha$$, $$\\beta$$ unsaturated carbonyl compounds in presence of NaOH followed by \nheat.</p>\n<p>Final Answer</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9kzsvf/cb9c3058-9f35-45d6-88a7-b833451e20d5/3d175bb0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9kzsvg.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9kzsvf/cb9c3058-9f35-45d6-88a7-b833451e20d5/3d175bb0-b372-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9kzsvg.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 10 English Explanation 5\"></p>\n<p>Hints :</p>\n<p>Ozonolysis of an unsaturated compound \nresults in replacing double bonds with \ncarbonyl group. The Zn in acetic acid is a \nreducing agent.</p>",
      "marks": 3,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "topic": "Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers"
    },
